      <hedline>
        <hl1>Art, Inside and Out</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Clive Wearlen letter on Aug 3 article suggests visitors to Solomon R Guggenheim Museum are drawn by more than just museum's architecture</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''With Huge Gift, the Whitney Is No Longer a Poor Cousin'' (front page, Aug. 3), you take a swipe at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum on Fifth Avenue, saying it ''attracts crowds simply because of its Frank Lloyd Wright building.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''With Huge Gift, the Whitney Is No Longer a Poor Cousin'' (front page, Aug. 3), you take a swipe at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum on Fifth Avenue, saying it ''attracts crowds simply because of its Frank Lloyd Wright building.''</p>
        <p>Yet in your June 30 magazine, you reported that the Guggenheim's ''Frank Gehry, Architect'' exhibition last year ''drew 397,032 visitors, more than any other show in the history of the museum.''</p>
        <p>Isn't it possible that some of the Guggenheim's visitors are actually attracted to what's inside the building?</p>
        <p>CLIVE WEARLEN  Brooklyn, Aug. 5, 2002</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
